body:
I just started playing with Ember and tried to replicate the todo app using the REST Adapter instead of the LocalStorage one. Overall it went well, however I noticed that the todo model is made in a way that every time the vale of the todo is changed (when editing it) the store commits the change. This is because the models `todoDidChange` function [observes the title attribute](https://github.com/tastejs/todomvc/blob/gh-pages/architecture-examples/emberjs/js/models/todo.js#L12) which in turn has a two-way binding to the value of the input box.

This works fine when using localStorage but when I tried to do the same the RESTful way it meant that the app sent a PUT request to the server every time the value on the text box was changed which caused some yankiness even if you typed moderately slow.

What I did was create a one-way binding instead from the model value to the text box (so it got populated with the the todo title) and updated it when the `insertNewLine` function ran:

```javascript
// edit_todo_view.js
Todos.EditTodoView = Ember.TextField.extend({
    ...

    valueBinding: Ember.Binding.oneWay('todo.title'),
    ...

    insertNewline: function () {
        this.set('controller.isEditing', false);
        this.set('todo.title', this.get('value'));
    },

    ...
});
```

This way the model is persisted only when you press enter. This also makes it possible to "reset" the todo title back to its previous value on blur, with the current implementation you have to re-type the whole thing again if you want the same functionality.

I'm wondering if it's something you'd like to incorporate on the Ember example, like I said I'm just starting with ember so there could be room for improvement but I think it's a nice way to also showcase how useful one-way bindings can be.

